'''MAA Foundation (Monayr Asha Aid Foundation)''' is a small [[non-governmental organization]], dedicated to promoting education in developing countries.<ref>[http://www.thelivemusicreport.com/2006/May/Bollywood_may06.html Corbett, Joyce: Monayr Asha (deepest desire)]</ref> MAA is based in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]], and currently runs projects in [[Bangladesh]] and in [[Uganda]].<ref>[http://videos.wittysparks.com/id/2756173459 MAA Fundraiser on SunTV] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718072237/http://videos.wittysparks.com/id/2756173459 |date=18 July 2011 }}</ref>

==Mission statement==

MAA was founded in 2006 with the goal of giving underprivileged children the possibility of a solid education which will provide them with a future of choices and opportunities. [[Child labour]] is a reality in many poor countries where families are dependent on their children’s labour to survive. MAA wants to change this dynamic and create the foundation of a sustainable [[socioeconomic development]] within small, poor communities, by giving young people a chance to improve their future lives and that of their community.<ref>[http://www.maaf.ca MAA Foundation Mission statement]</ref>

==Underlying Philosophy==

MAA was created out of the idea of using simple, personal resources and contacts for aid.<ref>[http://videos.wittysparks.com/id/2756173459 MAA Fundraiser on SunTV] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718072237/http://videos.wittysparks.com/id/2756173459 |date=18 July 2011 }}</ref> To raise funds, MAA works primarily with local artists in order to support local communities wherever possible. Fundraisers have featured musicians such as Gurpreet Chana, [[Devika Mathur]], TC Raas Band,<ref>[http://www.thelivemusicreport.com/2006/May/Bollywood_may06.html Corbett, Joyce: Monayr Asha (deepest desire)]</ref> or jazz saxophonist Sundar Viswanathan, who opened the 2006 MAA fundraiser Lula World.<ref>[http://www.yorku.ca/ylife/2006/06-June/06-01/viswanathan-060106.htm Ylife Newswire: Jazz saxophonist opens Lula World 2006]</ref>

==Activities==

At the moment MAA runs projects in [[Bangladesh]] and in [[Uganda]]. In Bangladesh, MAA provides scholarships for poor children in the slums of Chittagong, Bangladesh.<ref>[http://www.thelivemusicreport.com/2006/May/Bollywood_may06.html Corbett, Joyce: Monayr Asha (deepest desire)]</ref> Moreover, MAA is involved in the development of these communities, for instance through a project providing sustainable light sources, which give the school children the possibility to read in the evenings, rather than having to use kerosene candles which pollute the air.<ref>[http://www.citizenvoices.gg.ca/fr/blogs/rideau_hall/294 Godri, David: Le progrès de SWITCH et le programme de mentorat]{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In Uganda, MAA works together with Buwagga Senior Secondary School in Kasangati, Uganda. MAA supports Buwagga School by raising money to address the most urgent needs of the school, including crucial renovations and classroom supplies.<ref>[http://lula.xguru.com/events/lula.2006.07.19.pr.html Lula Lounge Media Release: Verao Vibes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718125752/http://lula.xguru.com/events/lula.2006.07.19.pr.html |date=18 July 2011 }}</ref>

